<p><b>Kevin Spacey Fowler</b> (born July 26, 1959) is an American actor. He began his career as a stage actor during the 1980s, obtaining supporting roles before gaining a <a href="/wiki/Leading_man" class="mw-redirect" title="Leading man">leading man</a> status in film and television. Spacey has received <a href="/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Kevin_Spacey" title="List of awards and nominations received by Kevin Spacey">various accolades</a> for his performances <a href="/wiki/Kevin_Spacey_on_screen_and_stage" title="Kevin Spacey on screen and stage">on stage and screen</a> including two <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Academy Awards</a>, a <a href="/wiki/BAFTA_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="BAFTA Award">BAFTA Award</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Tony_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a>, two <a href="/wiki/Laurence_Olivier_Awards" title="Laurence Olivier Awards">Laurence Olivier Awards</a>, and four <a href="/wiki/Screen_Actors_Guild_Awards" title="Screen Actors Guild Awards">Screen Actors Guild Awards</a>. He received nominations for a <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Grammy Award">Grammy Award</a> as well as twelve <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Primetime Emmy Award">Primetime Emmy Awards</a>. Spacey received a star on the <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame" title="Hollywood Walk of Fame">Hollywood Walk of Fame</a> in 1999, and was named an honorary Commander and Knight Commander of the <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">Order of the British Empire</a> in 2010 and 2015, respectively.
</p><p>His first film roles were in the <a href="/wiki/Mike_Nichols" title="Mike Nichols">Mike Nichols</a> films <i><a href="/wiki/Heartburn_(film)" title="Heartburn (film)">Heartburn</a></i> (1986) and <i><a href="/wiki/Working_Girl" title="Working Girl">Working Girl</a></i> (1988). Spacey received two <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Academy Awards</a>, the first for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor">Best Supporting Actor</a> for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Usual_Suspects" title="The Usual Suspects">The Usual Suspects</a></i> (1995) and the second for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor</a> for <i><a href="/wiki/American_Beauty_(1999_film)" title="American Beauty (1999 film)">American Beauty</a></i> (1999). He starred in the <a href="/wiki/Neo-noir" title="Neo-noir">neo-noir</a> crime film <i><a href="/wiki/L.A._Confidential_(film)" title="L.A. Confidential (film)">L.A. Confidential</a></i> earning a <a href="/wiki/BAFTA_Award_for_Best_Actor_in_a_Leading_Role" title="BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role">BAFTA Award for Best Actor in a Leading Role</a> nomination. His other notable films include <i><a href="/wiki/Glengarry_Glen_Ross_(film)" title="Glengarry Glen Ross (film)">Glengarry Glen Ross</a></i> (1992), <i><a href="/wiki/Swimming_with_Sharks" title="Swimming with Sharks">Swimming with Sharks</a></i> (1994), <i><a href="/wiki/Seven_(1995_film)" title="Seven (1995 film)">Se7en</a></i> (1995) <i><a href="/wiki/Pay_It_Forward_(film)" title="Pay It Forward (film)">Pay It Forward</a></i> (2000), <i><a href="/wiki/Superman_Returns" title="Superman Returns">Superman Returns</a></i> (2006), <i><a href="/wiki/Margin_Call" title="Margin Call">Margin Call</a></i> (2011), <i><a href="/wiki/Horrible_Bosses" title="Horrible Bosses">Horrible Bosses</a></i> (2011), <i><a href="/wiki/Baby_Driver" title="Baby Driver">Baby Driver</a></i> (2017). He directed <i><a href="/wiki/Albino_Alligator" title="Albino Alligator">Albino Alligator</a></i> (1996), and the musical biopic <i><a href="/wiki/Beyond_the_Sea_(2004_film)" title="Beyond the Sea (2004 film)">Beyond the Sea</a></i> (2004), starring as <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Darrin" class="mw-redirect" title="Bobby Darrin">Bobby Darrin</a> in the latter.
</p><p>In Broadway theatre, Spacey starred in the revival of <a href="/wiki/Eugene_O%27Neill" title="Eugene O&#39;Neill">Eugene O'Neill</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Long_Day%27s_Journey_into_Night" title="Long Day&#39;s Journey into Night">Long Day's Journey into Night</a></i> in 1986 alongside <a href="/wiki/Jack_Lemmon" title="Jack Lemmon">Jack Lemmon</a>. He won a <a href="/wiki/Tony_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a> in 1991 for his role in <i><a href="/wiki/Lost_in_Yonkers" title="Lost in Yonkers">Lost in Yonkers</a></i>. Spacey continued to act in theatre, receiving his second <a href="/wiki/Tony_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a> nomination and first <a href="/wiki/Laurence_Olivier_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Laurence Olivier Award">Laurence Olivier Award</a> win for his performance in the revival of <i><a href="/wiki/The_Iceman_Cometh" title="The Iceman Cometh">The Iceman Cometh</a></i> in 1999. In 2011, Spacey portrayed <a href="/wiki/Richard_III" class="mw-redirect" title="Richard III">Richard III</a> in <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_III_(play)" title="Richard III (play)">Richard III</a></i> and <a href="/wiki/Clarence_Darrow" title="Clarence Darrow">Clarence Darrow</a> in <i>Darrow</i> in 2015 in the <a href="/wiki/West_End_(theatre)" class="mw-redirect" title="West End (theatre)">West End</a>. He was the artistic director of the <a href="/wiki/Old_Vic" class="mw-redirect" title="Old Vic">Old Vic</a> theatre in London from 2004 until stepping down in mid-2015 and received the <a href="/wiki/Society_of_London_Theatre_Special_Award" title="Society of London Theatre Special Award">Laurence Olivier Award for Society of London Theatre Special Award</a>. In 2017, he hosted the <a href="/wiki/71st_Tony_Awards" title="71st Tony Awards">71st Tony Awards</a>.
</p><p>Spacey portrayed <a href="/wiki/Ron_Klain" title="Ron Klain">Ron Klain</a> in the <a href="/wiki/HBO" title="HBO">HBO</a> movie <i><a href="/wiki/Recount_(film)" title="Recount (film)">Recount</a></i> (2008) receiving a <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Lead_Actor_in_a_Limited_or_Anthology_Series_or_Movie" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited or Anthology Series or Movie">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Actor in a Limited Series or Movie</a> nomination. That same year, he produced the HBO film <i><a href="/wiki/Bernard_and_Doris" title="Bernard and Doris">Bernard and Doris</a></i> (2008) receiving a nomination for the <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Television_Movie" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie</a>. From 2013 to 2017, he starred as <a href="/wiki/Frank_Underwood_(House_of_Cards)" title="Frank Underwood (House of Cards)">Frank Underwood</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Netflix" title="Netflix">Netflix</a> political drama series <i><a href="/wiki/House_of_Cards_(American_TV_series)" title="House of Cards (American TV series)">House of Cards</a></i>, which won him a <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Actor_%E2%80%93_Television_Series_Drama" title="Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Television Series Drama">Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Television Series Drama</a> and two consecutive <a href="/wiki/Screen_Actors_Guild_Award_for_Outstanding_Performance_by_a_Male_Actor_in_a_Drama_Series" title="Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series">Screen Actors Guild Awards for Outstanding Actor in a Drama Series</a><sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> as well as five consecutive <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Lead_Actor_in_a_Drama_Series" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series</a> nominations.<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In October 2017, actor <a href="/wiki/Anthony_Rapp" title="Anthony Rapp">Anthony Rapp</a> accused Spacey of making a sexual advance toward him in 1986, when Rapp was 14. This was followed by a number of other high-profile accusations against Spacey. In the wake of these accusations, Netflix cut ties with Spacey, shelving his film <i>Gore</i> and removing him from the last season of <i>House of Cards</i>. His role as <a href="/wiki/J._Paul_Getty" title="J. Paul Getty">J. Paul Getty</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ridley_Scott" title="Ridley Scott">Ridley Scott</a>'s film <i><a href="/wiki/All_the_Money_in_the_World" title="All the Money in the World">All the Money in the World</a></i> (2017) was reshot with <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Plummer" title="Christopher Plummer">Christopher Plummer</a> in his place.<sup id="cite_ref-3" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-3">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-4">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Rapp's allegation was brought to trial in a 2022 lawsuit in New York, with the jury finding Spacey not liable.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> Spacey is facing criminal charges for an alleged sexual assault in the UK, with his trial set to begin in June 2023.<sup id="cite_ref-6" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-6">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<meta property="mw:PageProp/toc" />
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Early_life_and_education">Early life and education</span></h2>
<p>Kevin Spacey Fowler was born in <a href="/wiki/South_Orange,_New_Jersey" title="South Orange, New Jersey">South Orange, New Jersey</a>, to Kathleen Ann (<i>née</i> Knutson), a secretary, and Thomas Geoffrey Fowler, a <a href="/wiki/Technical_writer" title="Technical writer">technical writer</a> and data consultant.<sup id="cite_ref-name_8-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-name-8">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-dlrehioho_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dlrehioho-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup> His family relocated to <a href="/wiki/Southern_California" title="Southern California">Southern California</a> when he was four years old.<sup id="cite_ref-bio_10-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bio-10">&#91;10&#93;</a></sup> Spacey has a sister and an older brother, Randy Fowler, from whom Spacey is <a href="/wiki/Family_estrangement" title="Family estrangement">estranged</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11">&#91;11&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Randy_Fowler_Memoir_12-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Randy_Fowler_Memoir-12">&#91;12&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-Estranged_Brothers_13-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Estranged_Brothers-13">&#91;13&#93;</a></sup> His brother has stated that their father, whom he described as a racist "<a href="/wiki/Nazi" class="mw-redirect" title="Nazi">Nazi</a> supporter", was <a href="/wiki/Child_sexual_abuse" title="Child sexual abuse">sexually</a> and <a href="/wiki/Physical_abuse" title="Physical abuse">physically abusive</a>, and that Spacey shut down emotionally and became "very sly and smart" to avoid beatings.<sup id="cite_ref-independent_14-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-independent-14">&#91;14&#93;</a></sup> Spacey first addressed the matter in October 2022, saying that his father was "a <a href="/wiki/White_supremacy" title="White supremacy">white supremacist</a> and a <a href="/wiki/Neo-Nazism" title="Neo-Nazism">neo-Nazi</a>" who would call him "an <a href="/wiki/Faggot_(slang)" title="Faggot (slang)">F-word</a> that is very derogatory to the gay community".<sup id="cite_ref-LangFerme_15-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LangFerme-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-16" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-16">&#91;16&#93;</a></sup> He stated that this caused him to become extremely private about his personal life and was why he did not come out as gay earlier in his life.<sup id="cite_ref-LangFerme_15-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-LangFerme-15">&#91;15&#93;</a></sup> Spacey had previously described his father as "a very normal, middle-class man".<sup id="cite_ref-17" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-17">&#91;17&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey attended Northridge Military Academy, <a href="/wiki/Canoga_Park_High_School" title="Canoga Park High School">Canoga Park High School</a> in the 10th and 11th grades. He graduated <a href="/wiki/Valedictorian" title="Valedictorian">co-valedictorian</a> (along with <a href="/wiki/Mare_Winningham" title="Mare Winningham">Mare Winningham</a>) of the class of 1977 of <a href="/wiki/Chatsworth_High_School" title="Chatsworth High School">Chatsworth High School</a> in <a href="/wiki/Chatsworth,_Los_Angeles" title="Chatsworth, Los Angeles">Chatsworth</a>, <a href="/wiki/California" title="California">California</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-18" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-18">&#91;18&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-19">&#91;19&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-20" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-20">&#91;20&#93;</a></sup> At Chatsworth, Spacey starred in the school's senior production of <i><a href="/wiki/The_Sound_of_Music" title="The Sound of Music">The Sound of Music</a></i>, playing the part of <a href="/wiki/Georg_Ludwig_von_Trapp" class="mw-redirect" title="Georg Ludwig von Trapp">Captain Georg von Trapp</a>, with Winningham as <a href="/wiki/Maria_von_Trapp" title="Maria von Trapp">Maria von Trapp</a>. He started using his middle name "Spacey", which was his paternal grandmother's maiden name.<sup id="cite_ref-dlrehioho_9-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-dlrehioho-9">&#91;9&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-soroff_21-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-soroff-21">&#91;21&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey had tried to succeed as a comedian for several years before attending the <a href="/wiki/Juilliard_School" title="Juilliard School">Juilliard School</a> in New York City, as a member of <a href="/wiki/List_of_Juilliard_School_people" title="List of Juilliard School people">Group 12</a>, where he studied drama with teacher <a href="/wiki/Marian_Seldes" title="Marian Seldes">Marian Seldes</a><sup id="cite_ref-22" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-22">&#91;22&#93;</a></sup> between 1979 and 1981. During this time period, he performed stand-up comedy in <a href="/wiki/Bowling" title="Bowling">bowling</a> alley talent contests.<sup id="cite_ref-abc_23-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Career">Career</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Theatre">Theatre</span></h3>
<h4><span id="1981.E2.80.931986:_Career_beginnings_in_theatre"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="1981–1986:_Career_beginnings_in_theatre">1981–1986: Career beginnings in theatre</span></h4>
<p>Spacey's first professional stage appearance was as a <a href="/wiki/Spear_carrier" title="Spear carrier">spear carrier</a> in a <a href="/wiki/New_York_Shakespeare_Festival" class="mw-redirect" title="New York Shakespeare Festival">New York Shakespeare Festival</a> performance of <i><a href="/wiki/Henry_VI,_Part_1" title="Henry VI, Part 1">Henry VI, Part 1</a></i> in 1981.<sup id="cite_ref-24" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-24">&#91;24&#93;</a></sup> The following year, he made his first <a href="/wiki/Broadway_theatre" title="Broadway theatre">Broadway</a> appearance, as Oswald in a production of <a href="/wiki/Henrik_Ibsen" title="Henrik Ibsen">Henrik Ibsen</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Ghosts_(play)" title="Ghosts (play)">Ghosts</a></i>, starring <a href="/wiki/Liv_Ullmann" title="Liv Ullmann">Liv Ullmann</a> and director <a href="/wiki/John_Neville_(actor)" title="John Neville (actor)">John Neville</a>, which opened at the <a href="/wiki/Eisenhower_Theater" class="mw-redirect" title="Eisenhower Theater">Eisenhower Theater</a> in Washington's <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_Center" class="mw-redirect" title="Kennedy Center">Kennedy Center</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-25" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-25">&#91;25&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-26" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-26">&#91;26&#93;</a></sup> He then portrayed Philinte in <a href="/wiki/Moli%C3%A8re" title="Molière">Molière</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Misanthrope" title="The Misanthrope">The Misanthrope</a></i>. In 1984, Spacey appeared in a production of <a href="/wiki/David_Rabe" title="David Rabe">David Rabe</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Hurlyburly" title="Hurlyburly">Hurlyburly</a></i>, in which he rotated through each of the male parts (he would later play Mickey in the <a href="/wiki/Hurlyburly_(film)" title="Hurlyburly (film)">film version</a>). Next came <a href="/wiki/Anton_Chekhov" title="Anton Chekhov">Anton Chekhov</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/The_Seagull" title="The Seagull">The Seagull</a></i> alongside <a href="/wiki/David_Strathairn" title="David Strathairn">David Strathairn</a> and <a href="/wiki/Colleen_Dewhurst" title="Colleen Dewhurst">Colleen Dewhurst</a>. In 1986, Spacey appeared in a production of <i><a href="/wiki/Sleuth_(play)" title="Sleuth (play)">Sleuth</a></i> in a <a href="/wiki/New_Jersey" title="New Jersey">New Jersey</a> dinner theatre.<sup id="cite_ref-cornucopia_27-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cornucopia-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="1986.E2.80.931991:_Broadway_success_and_Tony_win"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="1986–1991:_Broadway_success_and_Tony_win">1986–1991: Broadway success and Tony win</span></h4>
<p>Spacey's prominence as a stage actor began in 1986, when he was cast opposite <a href="/wiki/Jack_Lemmon" title="Jack Lemmon">Jack Lemmon</a>, <a href="/wiki/Peter_Gallagher" title="Peter Gallagher">Peter Gallagher</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Bethel_Leslie" title="Bethel Leslie">Bethel Leslie</a>, as Jamie, the eldest Tyrone son, in <a href="/wiki/Jonathan_Miller" title="Jonathan Miller">Jonathan Miller</a>'s lauded production of <a href="/wiki/Eugene_O%27Neill" title="Eugene O&#39;Neill">Eugene O'Neill</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Long_Day%27s_Journey_into_Night" title="Long Day&#39;s Journey into Night">Long Day's Journey into Night</a></i>. Lemmon in particular would become a mentor to Spacey<sup id="cite_ref-parade_28-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-parade-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> and was invited, along with Spacey's high school drama teacher, to be present when Spacey received his star on the <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame" title="Hollywood Walk of Fame">Hollywood Walk of Fame</a> in 1999.<sup id="cite_ref-29" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-29">&#91;29&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey remained actively involved in the live theatre community. In 1991, he won a <a href="/wiki/Tony_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a> for his portrayal of Uncle Louie in <a href="/wiki/Neil_Simon" title="Neil Simon">Neil Simon</a>'s Broadway hit <i><a href="/wiki/Lost_in_Yonkers" title="Lost in Yonkers">Lost in Yonkers</a></i>. His father was unconvinced that Spacey could make a career for himself as an actor and did not change his mind until Spacey became well known.<sup id="cite_ref-abc_23-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-abc-23">&#91;23&#93;</a></sup> In 1999, Spacey won the <a href="/wiki/Laurence_Olivier_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor">Laurence Olivier Award for Best Actor</a> and earned another Tony Award nomination in 1999 for <i><a href="/wiki/The_Iceman_Cometh" title="The Iceman Cometh">The Iceman Cometh</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-30" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-30">&#91;30&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2003.E2.80.932015:_Artistic_director_of_the_Old_Vic"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2003–2015:_Artistic_director_of_the_Old_Vic">2003–2015: Artistic director of the Old Vic</span></h4>
<p>In February 2003, Spacey announced that he was to become the artistic director of the <a href="/wiki/Old_Vic" class="mw-redirect" title="Old Vic">Old Vic</a>, one of London's oldest theatres.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc20030203_31-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc20030203-31">&#91;31&#93;</a></sup> Appearing at a press conference with <a href="/wiki/Judi_Dench" title="Judi Dench">Judi Dench</a> and <a href="/wiki/Elton_John" title="Elton John">Elton John</a>, Spacey promised both to appear on stage and to bring in big-name talent.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc20030206_32-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc20030206-32">&#91;32&#93;</a></sup> He undertook to remain in the post for a full ten years. The Old Vic Theatre Company staged shows eight months out of the year. Spacey's first season started in September 2004, opening with the British premiere of the play <i><a href="/wiki/Cloaca_(film)" title="Cloaca (film)">Cloaca</a></i> by <a href="/wiki/Maria_Goos" class="mw-redirect" title="Maria Goos">Maria Goos</a>, directed by Spacey, which opened to mixed reviews.<sup id="cite_ref-firstseason_33-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firstseason-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup> In the 2005 season, Spacey made his UK Shakespearean debut, to good notices, in the <a href="/wiki/Richard_II_of_England" title="Richard II of England">title role</a> of <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_II_(play)" title="Richard II (play)">Richard II</a></i>, directed by <a href="/wiki/Trevor_Nunn" title="Trevor Nunn">Trevor Nunn</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-firstseason_33-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-firstseason-33">&#91;33&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On June 16, 2016, Spacey was awarded an <a href="https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/Special:Search/honorary" class="extiw" title="wikt:Special:Search/honorary">honorary</a> <a href="/wiki/Knighthood" class="mw-redirect" title="Knighthood">knighthood</a> for his services to theatre, arts education, and international culture in the <a href="/wiki/2015_Queen%27s_Birthday_Honours" class="mw-redirect" title="2015 Queen&#39;s Birthday Honours">2015 Queen's Birthday Honours</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-34" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-34">&#91;34&#93;</a></sup> The honour, <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">Knight Commander of the Order of the British Empire</a>, was given at <a href="/wiki/Clarence_House" title="Clarence House">Clarence House</a> by then-<a href="/wiki/Charles_III_of_the_United_Kingdom" class="mw-redirect" title="Charles III of the United Kingdom">Prince Charles</a>. As a non-<a href="/wiki/Commonwealth_Realm" class="mw-redirect" title="Commonwealth Realm">Commonwealth Realm</a> citizen, the award is honorary and he is not entitled to the <a href="/wiki/Honorific" title="Honorific">honorific</a> "Sir".<sup id="cite_ref-35" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-35">&#91;35&#93;</a></sup> Spacey had previously been awarded the lesser rank of honorary Commander of the Order of the British Empire (CBE) for services to drama in 2010.<sup id="cite_ref-36" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-36">&#91;36&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey was a patron of the <a href="/wiki/Shakespeare_Schools_Festival" title="Shakespeare Schools Festival">Shakespeare Schools Festival</a>, a charity that enables school children across the UK to perform Shakespeare in professional theatres. He also sits on the board of directors of the <a href="/wiki/Motion_Picture_and_Television_Fund" class="mw-redirect" title="Motion Picture and Television Fund">Motion Picture and Television Fund</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-37" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-37">&#91;37&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In mid 2006, Spacey said that he was having the time of his life working at the Old Vic; at that point in his career, he said, he was "trying to do things now that are much bigger and outside [myself]".<sup id="cite_ref-nyt-oldvic_38-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-oldvic-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> Spacey performed in productions of <i>National Anthems</i> by Dennis McIntyre, and <i><a href="/wiki/The_Philadelphia_Story_(play)" title="The Philadelphia Story (play)">The Philadelphia Story</a></i> by <a href="/wiki/Philip_Barry" title="Philip Barry">Philip Barry</a>, in which he played C.K. Dexter Haven, the <a href="/wiki/Cary_Grant" title="Cary Grant">Cary Grant</a> role in the <a href="/wiki/The_Philadelphia_Story_(film)" title="The Philadelphia Story (film)">film version</a>. Critics applauded Spacey for taking on the management of a theatre, but noted that while his acting was impressive, his skills and judgment as a producer/manager had yet to develop.<sup id="cite_ref-richardiii_39-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-richardiii-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In the 2006 season, Spacey suffered a major setback with a production of <a href="/wiki/Arthur_Miller" title="Arthur Miller">Arthur Miller</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Resurrection_Blues" title="Resurrection Blues">Resurrection Blues</a></i>, directed by <a href="/wiki/Robert_Altman" title="Robert Altman">Robert Altman</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-bbc20060413_40-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-bbc20060413-40">&#91;40&#93;</a></sup> Despite an all-star cast (including <a href="/wiki/Matthew_Modine" title="Matthew Modine">Matthew Modine</a> and future <i>House of Cards</i> co-star <a href="/wiki/Neve_Campbell" title="Neve Campbell">Neve Campbell</a>) and the pedigree of Miller's script, Spacey's decision to lure Altman to the stage proved disastrous: after a fraught rehearsal period, the play opened to a critical panning, and closed after only a few weeks.<sup id="cite_ref-nyt-oldvic_38-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-nyt-oldvic-38">&#91;38&#93;</a></sup> Later in the year, Spacey starred in <a href="/wiki/Eugene_O%27Neill" title="Eugene O&#39;Neill">Eugene O'Neill</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/A_Moon_for_the_Misbegotten" title="A Moon for the Misbegotten">A Moon for the Misbegotten</a></i>, along with <a href="/wiki/Colm_Meaney" title="Colm Meaney">Colm Meaney</a> and <a href="/wiki/Eve_Best" title="Eve Best">Eve Best</a>. The play received excellent reviews for Spacey and Best, and was transferred to Broadway in 2007. For the spring part of the 2007–08 season, <a href="/wiki/Jeff_Goldblum" title="Jeff Goldblum">Jeff Goldblum</a> and <a href="/wiki/Laura_Michelle_Kelly" title="Laura Michelle Kelly">Laura Michelle Kelly</a> joined Spacey as the three characters in <a href="/wiki/David_Mamet" title="David Mamet">David Mamet</a>'s 1988 play <i><a href="/wiki/Speed-the-Plow" title="Speed-the-Plow">Speed-the-Plow</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-stage20071210_41-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-stage20071210-41">&#91;41&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2009, he directed the premiere of <a href="/wiki/Joe_Sutton" title="Joe Sutton">Joe Sutton</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Complicit_(play)" title="Complicit (play)">Complicit</a></i>, with <a href="/wiki/Richard_Dreyfuss" title="Richard Dreyfuss">Richard Dreyfuss</a>, <a href="/wiki/David_Suchet" title="David Suchet">David Suchet</a> and <a href="/wiki/Elizabeth_McGovern" title="Elizabeth McGovern">Elizabeth McGovern</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-richardiii_39-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-richardiii-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> Later that year, Trevor Nunn directed Spacey in a revival of <i><a href="/wiki/Inherit_the_Wind_(play)" title="Inherit the Wind (play)">Inherit the Wind</a></i>. Spacey played defense lawyer Henry Drummond, a role that was made famous by <a href="/wiki/Spencer_Tracy" title="Spencer Tracy">Spencer Tracy</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Inherit_the_Wind_(1960_film)" title="Inherit the Wind (1960 film)">1960 film of the same name</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-richardiii_39-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-richardiii-39">&#91;39&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Sam_Mendes" title="Sam Mendes">Sam Mendes</a> directed Spacey in Shakespeare's <i><a href="/wiki/Richard_III_(play)" title="Richard III (play)">Richard III</a></i>; Spacey played the <a href="/wiki/Richard_III_of_England" title="Richard III of England">title role</a>. The show began in June 2011, commencing a worldwide tour culminating in New York in early 2012.<sup id="cite_ref-42" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-42">&#91;42&#93;</a></sup> In March 2014, it was announced that Spacey would star in a one-man play at the Old Vic to celebrate his ten years as artistic director. He took on the part of <a href="/wiki/Clarence_Darrow" title="Clarence Darrow">Clarence Darrow</a> in the play.<sup id="cite_ref-43" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-43">&#91;43&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Film">Film</span></h3>
<h4><span id="1986.E2.80.931994:_Early_roles_and_breakthrough"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="1986–1994:_Early_roles_and_breakthrough">1986–1994: Early roles and breakthrough</span></h4>
<p>In 1986, Spacey made his first film appearance in <a href="/wiki/Mike_Nichols" title="Mike Nichols">Mike Nichols</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Heartburn_(film)" title="Heartburn (film)">Heartburn</a></i> starring <a href="/wiki/Meryl_Streep" title="Meryl Streep">Meryl Streep</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Jack_Nicholson" title="Jack Nicholson">Jack Nicholson</a>. Spacey plays a small role credited as a subway thief. In 1988 Spacey also briefly appeared in another Nichols film, <i><a href="/wiki/Working_Girl" title="Working Girl">Working Girl</a></i>, as businessman Bob Speck. Some of Spacey's other early roles include a widowed millionaire on <i><a href="/wiki/L.A._Law" title="L.A. Law">L.A. Law</a></i>; the television miniseries <i><a href="/wiki/The_Murder_of_Mary_Phagan" title="The Murder of Mary Phagan">The Murder of Mary Phagan</a></i> (1988), opposite Lemmon; and the comedy <i><a href="/wiki/See_No_Evil,_Hear_No_Evil" title="See No Evil, Hear No Evil">See No Evil, Hear No Evil</a></i> (1989). Spacey quickly developed a reputation as a <a href="/wiki/Character_actor" title="Character actor">character actor</a>, and was cast in bigger roles, including the malevolent office manager in the ensemble film adaptation of the <a href="/wiki/David_Mamet" title="David Mamet">David Mamet</a> play <i><a href="/wiki/Glengarry_Glen_Ross_(film)" title="Glengarry Glen Ross (film)">Glengarry Glen Ross</a></i> (1992) starring <a href="/wiki/Al_Pacino" title="Al Pacino">Al Pacino</a>, as well as news reporter Harry Kingsley in a film based on a 1917 <a href="/wiki/Sled_dog_racing" title="Sled dog racing">dog sled race</a> <i><a href="/wiki/Iron_Will" title="Iron Will">Iron Will</a></i> (1994) directed by <a href="/wiki/Charles_Haid" title="Charles Haid">Charles Haid</a>. Spacey also played one-half of a bickering <a href="/wiki/Connecticut" title="Connecticut">Connecticut</a> couple alongside <a href="/wiki/Judy_Davis" title="Judy Davis">Judy Davis</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Dark_comedy" class="mw-redirect" title="Dark comedy">dark comedy</a> Christmas film <i><a href="/wiki/The_Ref" title="The Ref">The Ref</a></i> (1994), and a malicious Hollywood studio boss in the satire <i><a href="/wiki/Swimming_with_Sharks" title="Swimming with Sharks">Swimming with Sharks</a></i> (1995).
</p>
<h4><span id="1995.E2.80.931999:_Rise_to_stardom_and_awards_success"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="1995–1999:_Rise_to_stardom_and_awards_success">1995–1999: Rise to stardom and awards success</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tleft"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_(48171134437).jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg/170px-Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="237" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg/255px-Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg/340px-Kevin_Spacey_%2848171134437%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="734" data-file-height="1024" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_(48171134437).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Spacey in 1996</div></div></div>
<p>Spacey's performance as the enigmatic criminal <a href="/wiki/Keyser_S%C3%B6ze" title="Keyser Söze">Verbal Kint</a> in <a href="/wiki/Bryan_Singer" title="Bryan Singer">Bryan Singer</a>'s 1995 <a href="/wiki/Neo-noir" title="Neo-noir">neo-noir</a> film <i><a href="/wiki/The_Usual_Suspects" title="The Usual Suspects">The Usual Suspects</a></i> won him the <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor">Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-tca_44-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tca-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1995, Spacey also appeared in the <a href="/wiki/David_Fincher" title="David Fincher">David Fincher</a> detective thriller <i><a href="/wiki/Seven_(1995_film)" title="Seven (1995 film)">Seven</a></i>, making a sudden entrance late in the film as <a href="/wiki/Serial_killer" title="Serial killer">serial killer</a> John Doe after going uncredited and unmentioned in the film's advertisements and opening credits. His work in <i>Seven</i>, <i>The Usual Suspects</i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Outbreak_(film)" title="Outbreak (film)">Outbreak</a></i> earned him Best Supporting Actor honors at the 1995 <a href="/wiki/Society_of_Texas_Film_Critics_Awards_1995" title="Society of Texas Film Critics Awards 1995">Society of Texas Film Critics Awards</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-aas951230_45-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-aas951230-45">&#91;45&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-ac960105_46-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ac960105-46">&#91;46&#93;</a></sup> Spacey played an egomaniacal <a href="/wiki/District_attorney" title="District attorney">district attorney</a> in <i><a href="/wiki/A_Time_to_Kill_(1996_film)" title="A Time to Kill (1996 film)">A Time to Kill</a></i> (1996) and founded <a href="/wiki/Trigger_Street_Productions" title="Trigger Street Productions">Trigger Street Productions</a> in 1997 with the purpose of producing and developing entertainment across various media. Spacey made his directorial debut with the film <i><a href="/wiki/Albino_Alligator" title="Albino Alligator">Albino Alligator</a></i> (1996). The film was a <a href="/wiki/Box_office_bomb" class="mw-redirect" title="Box office bomb">box office bomb</a>, grossing $339,379 with a budget of $6&#160;million, but critics praised Spacey's direction. He also voiced Hopper in the animated film <i><a href="/wiki/A_Bug%27s_Life" title="A Bug&#39;s Life">A Bug's Life</a></i> (1998).<sup id="cite_ref-cornucopia_27-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-cornucopia-27">&#91;27&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Throughout his career, Spacey has been well known for playing villains; he remarked in 2013: "I think people just like me evil for some reason. They want me to be a son of a bitch."<sup id="cite_ref-47" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-47">&#91;47&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1999, Spacey acted alongside <a href="/wiki/Annette_Bening" title="Annette Bening">Annette Bening</a> in <a href="/wiki/Sam_Mendes" title="Sam Mendes">Sam Mendes</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/American_Beauty_(1999_film)" title="American Beauty (1999 film)">American Beauty</a></i>. In the film he played the role of Lester Burnham, a depressed suburban father and advertising executive who becomes attracted to his teenage daughter's best friend. For this role, Spacey won his second <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Academy Award">Oscar</a>, this time for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor in a Leading Role</a>. In his acceptance speech he dedicated his Oscar to <a href="/wiki/Jack_Lemmon" title="Jack Lemmon">Jack Lemmon</a>, praising him as an influence, mentor, and father figure. He also stated, "[Lemmon's] performance in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Apartment" title="The Apartment">The Apartment</a></i> stands as one of the finest we've ever had".<sup id="cite_ref-48" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-48">&#91;48&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-49" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-49">&#91;49&#93;</a></sup> That same year, he was honored with a star on the <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame" title="Hollywood Walk of Fame">Hollywood Walk of Fame</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-50" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-50">&#91;50&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2000.E2.80.932009:_Continued_work"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2000–2009:_Continued_work">2000–2009: Continued work</span></h4>
<p>Spacey played a physically and emotionally scarred grade school teacher in <i><a href="/wiki/Pay_It_Forward_(film)" title="Pay It Forward (film)">Pay It Forward</a></i> (2000), a patient in a mental institution who may or may not be an <a href="/wiki/Extraterrestrial_life" title="Extraterrestrial life">alien</a> in <i><a href="/wiki/K-PAX_(film)" title="K-PAX (film)">K-Pax</a></i> (2001), and singer <a href="/wiki/Bobby_Darin" title="Bobby Darin">Bobby Darin</a> in <i><a href="/wiki/Beyond_the_Sea_(2004_film)" title="Beyond the Sea (2004 film)">Beyond the Sea</a></i> (2004). The latter was a lifelong dream project for Spacey, who took on co-writing, directing, co-producing and starring duties in the biography/musical about Darin's life, career and relationship with actress <a href="/wiki/Sandra_Dee" title="Sandra Dee">Sandra Dee</a>. Facing little interest for backing in the U.S., Spacey went to the United Kingdom and Germany for funding. Almost all of the film was made in <a href="/wiki/Berlin" title="Berlin">Berlin</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-parade_28-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-parade-28">&#91;28&#93;</a></sup> Spacey provided his own vocals on the film's soundtrack and appeared in several tribute concerts around the time of its release. Spacey received mostly positive reviews for his singing, as well as a <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe" class="mw-redirect" title="Golden Globe">Golden Globe</a> nomination for his performance. However, reviewers debated the age disparity between Spacey and Darin, noting that Spacey was too old to convincingly portray Darin, particularly during the early stages of the singer's life depicted in the film.<sup id="cite_ref-51" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-51">&#91;51&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2006, Spacey played <a href="/wiki/Lex_Luthor" title="Lex Luthor">Lex Luthor</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Bryan_Singer" title="Bryan Singer">Bryan Singer</a> <a href="/wiki/Superhero" title="Superhero">superhero</a> film <i><a href="/wiki/Superman_Returns" title="Superman Returns">Superman Returns</a></i> starring <a href="/wiki/Brandon_Routh" title="Brandon Routh">Brandon Routh</a>. He was to return for its 2009 sequel, but the series was instead rebooted with the 2013 film <i><a href="/wiki/Man_of_Steel_(film)" title="Man of Steel (film)">Man of Steel</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-52" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-52">&#91;52&#93;</a></sup> Spacey also appeared in <i><a href="/wiki/Edison_(film)" title="Edison (film)">Edison</a></i>, which received a <a href="/wiki/Direct-to-video" title="Direct-to-video">direct-to-video</a> release in 2006.<sup id="cite_ref-53" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-53">&#91;53&#93;</a></sup> The film was released in theaters in <a href="/wiki/Netherlands" title="Netherlands">Netherlands</a> on March 12, 2006.
</p><p>In 2008, Spacey played a <a href="/wiki/Massachusetts_Institute_of_Technology" title="Massachusetts Institute of Technology">Massachusetts Institute of Technology</a> (MIT) lecturer in the film <i><a href="/wiki/21_(2008_film)" title="21 (2008 film)">21</a></i>. The film is based on <a href="/wiki/Ben_Mezrich" title="Ben Mezrich">Ben Mezrich</a>'s best seller <i><a href="/wiki/Bringing_Down_the_House_(book)" title="Bringing Down the House (book)">Bringing Down the House: The Inside Story of Six MIT Students Who Took Vegas for Millions</a></i>, a story of student MIT <a href="/wiki/Card-counting" class="mw-redirect" title="Card-counting">card-counters</a> who used <a href="/wiki/Mathematical_probability" class="mw-redirect" title="Mathematical probability">mathematical probability</a> to aid them in card games such as <a href="/wiki/Blackjack" title="Blackjack">blackjack</a>. In early 2010, Spacey went to China to star in writer-director <a href="/wiki/Dayyan_Eng" title="Dayyan Eng">Dayyan Eng</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Black_comedy" title="Black comedy">black comedy</a> film <i><a href="/wiki/Inseparable_(film)" title="Inseparable (film)">Inseparable</a></i>, becoming the first Hollywood actor to star in a fully Chinese-funded film.<sup id="cite_ref-54" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-54">&#91;54&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2011.E2.80.932016:_Independent_films_and_comedies"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2011–2016:_Independent_films_and_comedies">2011–2016: Independent films and comedies</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:172px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_(Berlin_Film_Festival_2011).jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg/170px-Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="170" height="203" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg/255px-Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2d/Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg/340px-Kevin_Spacey_%28Berlin_Film_Festival_2011%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2194" data-file-height="2621" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_(Berlin_Film_Festival_2011).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Spacey at the <a href="/wiki/Berlin_International_Film_Festival" title="Berlin International Film Festival">Berlin Film Festival</a> 2011</div></div></div>
<p>In 2011, Spacey starred in <a href="/wiki/J.C._Chandor" class="mw-redirect" title="J.C. Chandor">J.C. Chandor</a>'s financial thriller <i><a href="/wiki/Margin_Call" title="Margin Call">Margin Call</a></i> alongside <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bettany" title="Paul Bettany">Paul Bettany</a>, <a href="/wiki/Jeremy_Irons" title="Jeremy Irons">Jeremy Irons</a>, <a href="/wiki/Zachary_Quinto" title="Zachary Quinto">Zachary Quinto</a>, <a href="/wiki/Demi_Moore" title="Demi Moore">Demi Moore</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Stanley_Tucci" title="Stanley Tucci">Stanley Tucci</a>. The story at large takes place over a 24-hour period at a large <a href="/wiki/Wall_Street" title="Wall Street">Wall Street</a> <a href="/wiki/Investment_banking" title="Investment banking">investment bank</a> during the initial stages of the <a href="/wiki/Financial_crisis_of_2007%E2%80%932008" class="mw-redirect" title="Financial crisis of 2007–2008">financial crisis of 2007–2008</a>. The film, which focuses on the actions taken by a group of employees during the subsequent financial collapse, made its debut at the <a href="/wiki/Sundance_Film_Festival" title="Sundance Film Festival">Sundance Film Festival</a> to critical acclaim. Spacey received the <a href="/wiki/Independent_Spirit_Robert_Altman_Award" title="Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award">Independent Spirit Robert Altman Award</a> along with the cast. That same year, Spacey co-starred in the black comedy film <i><a href="/wiki/Horrible_Bosses" title="Horrible Bosses">Horrible Bosses</a></i>, which grossed over $209.6&#160;million at the box office.<sup id="cite_ref-55" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-55">&#91;55&#93;</a></sup> In 2013 he executive-produced the biographical survival thriller film <i><a href="/wiki/Captain_Phillips_(film)" title="Captain Phillips (film)">Captain Phillips</a></i>, which was nominated for the <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Picture" title="Academy Award for Best Picture">Academy Award for Best Picture</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-oscarnom_56-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-oscarnom-56">&#91;56&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-oscarwin_57-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-oscarwin-57">&#91;57&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>He starred as President <a href="/wiki/Richard_Nixon" title="Richard Nixon">Richard Nixon</a> in the comedy-drama <i><a href="/wiki/Elvis_%26_Nixon" title="Elvis &amp; Nixon">Elvis &amp; Nixon</a></i> (2016), which is based on the meeting that took place between Nixon and singer <a href="/wiki/Elvis_Presley" title="Elvis Presley">Elvis Presley</a> (<a href="/wiki/Michael_Shannon" title="Michael Shannon">Michael Shannon</a>) in December 1970 wherein Presley requested Nixon swear him in as an undercover agent in the <a href="/wiki/Bureau_of_Narcotics_and_Dangerous_Drugs" title="Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs">Bureau of Narcotics and Dangerous Drugs</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-58" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-58">&#91;58&#93;</a></sup> He next starred in the comedy film <i><a href="/wiki/Nine_Lives_(2016_film)" title="Nine Lives (2016 film)">Nine Lives</a></i>, as a man trapped in the body of a cat.<sup id="cite_ref-59" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-59">&#91;59&#93;</a></sup> The film was released on August 5, 2016.<sup id="cite_ref-60" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-60">&#91;60&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In January 2016 it was announced that <a href="/wiki/Relativity_Media" title="Relativity Media">Relativity Media</a>, which was just emerging from <a href="/wiki/Chapter_11,_Title_11,_United_States_Code" title="Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code">Chapter 11 bankruptcy</a>,<sup id="cite_ref-61" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-61">&#91;61&#93;</a></sup> had acquired Trigger Street Productions and that Spacey would become chairman of <a href="/wiki/Relativity_Media#Relativity_Studios" title="Relativity Media">Relativity Studios</a>, while Dana Brunetti would become the studio's president.<sup id="cite_ref-62" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-62">&#91;62&#93;</a></sup> Spacey called the move "an incredible opportunity to make great entertainment" and said he considered it the "next evolution in my career".<sup id="cite_ref-63" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-63">&#91;63&#93;</a></sup> However, when the paperwork for the studio was filed for the court, it emerged that Spacey had opted out of assuming the chairmanship of the studios,<sup id="cite_ref-64" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-64">&#91;64&#93;</a></sup> and by the end of 2016 Brunetti had also left Relativity, while both remained executive producers on <i>House of Cards</i> and <i><a href="/wiki/Manhunt:_Unabomber" class="mw-redirect" title="Manhunt: Unabomber">Manifesto</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-65" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-65">&#91;65&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2017.E2.80.93present:_Career_controversy"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2017–present:_Career_controversy">2017–present: Career controversy</span></h4>
<p>In March 2017, it was announced that Spacey would portray <a href="/wiki/J._Paul_Getty" title="J. Paul Getty">J. Paul Getty</a> in <a href="/wiki/Ridley_Scott" title="Ridley Scott">Ridley Scott</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/All_the_Money_in_the_World" title="All the Money in the World">All the Money in the World</a></i>.<sup id="cite_ref-66" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-66">&#91;66&#93;</a></sup> He shot his role in the film in ten days over the summer of 2017. However, owing to the <a href="/wiki/Sexual_assault" title="Sexual assault">sexual assault</a> allegations against Spacey, it was announced on November 8, 2017, that all of his footage would be excised,<sup id="cite_ref-67" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-67">&#91;67&#93;</a></sup> and that <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Plummer" title="Christopher Plummer">Christopher Plummer</a> would replace Spacey as Getty in <a href="/wiki/Pick-up_(filmmaking)" title="Pick-up (filmmaking)">reshoots</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-DeadlineA_081117_68-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-DeadlineA_081117-68">&#91;68&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-69" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-69">&#91;69&#93;</a></sup> In spite of the very tight schedule, <a href="/wiki/TriStar_Pictures" title="TriStar Pictures">TriStar Pictures</a> completed the new version of the film in time for a December 25 release.<sup id="cite_ref-70" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-70">&#91;70&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-71" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-71">&#91;71&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey appeared in the film <i><a href="/wiki/Billionaire_Boys_Club_(2018_film)" title="Billionaire Boys Club (2018 film)">Billionaire Boys Club</a></i>, which had a <a href="/wiki/Limited_release" class="mw-redirect" title="Limited release">limited release</a> on August 17, 2018.<sup id="cite_ref-72" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-72">&#91;72&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-73" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-73">&#91;73&#93;</a></sup> <a href="/wiki/Vertical_Entertainment" title="Vertical Entertainment">Vertical Entertainment</a> stated that they would be taking no action to remove Spacey from the film, as it had been completed in late 2016, prior to the allegations made in October 2017.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r996844942">.mw-parser-output .templatequote{overflow:hidden;margin:1em 0;padding:0 40px}.mw-parser-output .templatequote .templatequotecite{line-height:1.5em;text-align:left;padding-left:1.6em;margin-top:0}</style><blockquote class="templatequote"><p>We don't condone sexual harassment on any level and we fully support victims of it. At the same time, this is neither an easy nor insensitive decision to release this film in theatres, but we believe in giving the cast, as well as hundreds of crew members who worked hard on the film, the chance to see their final product reach audiences.<sup id="cite_ref-74" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-74">&#91;74&#93;</a></sup></p><div class="templatequotecite">—&#8201;<cite><i>Vertical Entertainment on their decision to release the film without any cuts or changes</i></cite></div></blockquote>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Television">Television</span></h3>
<h4><span id="1987.E2.80.931994:_Television_debut_and_early_roles"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="1987–1994:_Television_debut_and_early_roles">1987–1994: Television debut and early roles</span></h4>
<p>In 1987, Spacey made his first major television appearance in the second-season premiere of <i><a href="/wiki/Crime_Story_(U.S._TV_series)" class="mw-redirect" title="Crime Story (U.S. TV series)">Crime Story</a></i>, playing a <a href="/wiki/Kennedy_family" title="Kennedy family">Kennedy-esque</a> American senator. That same year he appeared in spy thriller series <i><a href="/wiki/The_Equalizer_(1985_TV_series)" title="The Equalizer (1985 TV series)">The Equalizer</a></i> as Detective Sergeant Cole in the episode "Solo". He earned a fan base after playing the criminally insane arms dealer Mel Profitt on the television series <i><a href="/wiki/Wiseguy_(TV_series)" title="Wiseguy (TV series)">Wiseguy</a></i> (1988).<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2003.E2.80.932012:_HBO_projects_and_other_work"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2003–2012:_HBO_projects_and_other_work">2003–2012: HBO projects and other work</span></h4>
<p>Spacey hosted <i><a href="/wiki/Saturday_Night_Live" title="Saturday Night Live">Saturday Night Live</a></i> twice: first in 1997 with musical guest <a href="/wiki/Beck" title="Beck">Beck</a> and special guests <a href="/wiki/Michael_Palin" title="Michael Palin">Michael Palin</a> and <a href="/wiki/John_Cleese" title="John Cleese">John Cleese</a> from <i><a href="/wiki/Monty_Python%27s_Flying_Circus" title="Monty Python&#39;s Flying Circus">Monty Python's Flying Circus</a></i> and again in May 2006 with musical guest <a href="/wiki/Nelly_Furtado" title="Nelly Furtado">Nelly Furtado</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup>
</p><p>In 2008 Spacey starred as <a href="/wiki/Ron_Klain" title="Ron Klain">Ron Klain</a> in the <a href="/wiki/HBO" title="HBO">HBO</a> original political drama film <i><a href="/wiki/Recount_(film)" title="Recount (film)">Recount</a></i> revolving around <a href="/wiki/2000_United_States_presidential_election_recount_in_Florida" title="2000 United States presidential election recount in Florida">Florida's vote recount</a> during the <a href="/wiki/2000_United_States_presidential_election" title="2000 United States presidential election">2000 United States presidential election</a> between <a href="/wiki/George_W._Bush" title="George W. Bush">George W. Bush</a> and <a href="/wiki/Al_Gore" title="Al Gore">Al Gore</a>. The film was written by <a href="/wiki/Danny_Strong" title="Danny Strong">Danny Strong</a> and directed by <a href="/wiki/Jay_Roach" title="Jay Roach">Jay Roach</a> and starred <a href="/wiki/Bob_Balaban" title="Bob Balaban">Bob Balaban</a>, <a href="/wiki/Laura_Dern" title="Laura Dern">Laura Dern</a>, <a href="/wiki/John_Hurt" title="John Hurt">John Hurt</a>, <a href="/wiki/Denis_Leary" title="Denis Leary">Denis Leary</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Tom_Wilkinson" title="Tom Wilkinson">Tom Wilkinson</a>. The television film won three <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Primetime Emmy Award">Primetime Emmy Awards</a>, including <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Television_Movie" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie">Outstanding Television Movie</a>. For his performance in the film, Spacey was nominated for the <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Lead_Actor_in_a_Limited_Series_or_Movie" class="mw-redirect" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Limited Series or Movie</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Actor_%E2%80%93_Miniseries_or_Television_Film" title="Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Miniseries or Television Film">Golden Globe Award for Best Actor in a Miniseries or Television Film</a>. That same year Spacey produced the TV movie <i><a href="/wiki/Bernard_and_Doris" title="Bernard and Doris">Bernard and Doris</a></i>, an HBO semi-fictionalized account of the relationship that developed between socialite <a href="/wiki/Beneficiary" title="Beneficiary">heiress</a> and philanthropist <a href="/wiki/Doris_Duke" title="Doris Duke">Doris Duke</a> and her self-destructive Irish butler <a href="/wiki/Bernard_Lafferty_(butler)" class="mw-redirect" title="Bernard Lafferty (butler)">Bernard Lafferty</a> later in her life. The film starred <a href="/wiki/Ralph_Fiennes" title="Ralph Fiennes">Ralph Fiennes</a> and <a href="/wiki/Susan_Sarandon" title="Susan Sarandon">Susan Sarandon</a> and was directed by <a href="/wiki/Bob_Balaban" title="Bob Balaban">Bob Balaban</a>. The film premiered at the <a href="/wiki/Hamptons_International_Film_Festival" title="Hamptons International Film Festival">Hamptons International Film Festival</a> to critical acclaim, and Spacey was nominated for the <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Television_Movie" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Television Movie</a>.<sup class="noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">&#91;<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (October 2022)">citation needed</span></a></i>&#93;</sup> Spacey portrayed the <a href="/wiki/Antagonist" title="Antagonist">antagonist</a> Jonathan Irons in the 2014 video game <i><a href="/wiki/Call_of_Duty:_Advanced_Warfare" title="Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare">Call of Duty: Advanced Warfare</a></i> through <a href="/wiki/Motion_capture" title="Motion capture">motion capture</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-CoDAW_75-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CoDAW-75">&#91;75&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>Spacey is well known in Hollywood for his <a href="/wiki/Impressionist_(entertainment)" title="Impressionist (entertainment)">impressions</a>. When he appeared on <i><a href="/wiki/Inside_the_Actors_Studio" title="Inside the Actors Studio">Inside the Actors Studio</a></i>, he imitated (at host <a href="/wiki/James_Lipton" title="James Lipton">James Lipton</a>'s request) Jack Lemmon, <a href="/wiki/James_Stewart" title="James Stewart">James Stewart</a>, <a href="/wiki/Johnny_Carson" title="Johnny Carson">Johnny Carson</a>, <a href="/wiki/Katharine_Hepburn" title="Katharine Hepburn">Katharine Hepburn</a>, <a href="/wiki/Clint_Eastwood" title="Clint Eastwood">Clint Eastwood</a>, <a href="/wiki/John_Gielgud" title="John Gielgud">John Gielgud</a>, <a href="/wiki/Marlon_Brando" title="Marlon Brando">Marlon Brando</a>, <a href="/wiki/Christopher_Walken" title="Christopher Walken">Christopher Walken</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Al_Pacino" title="Al Pacino">Al Pacino</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-tca_44-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-tca-44">&#91;44&#93;</a></sup> On <i><a href="/wiki/The_Tonight_Show_with_Jimmy_Fallon" class="mw-redirect" title="The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon">The Tonight Show with Jimmy Fallon</a></i>, Spacey admitted to using his vocal skills as a young actor in New York City to pretend to be Carson's son in order to obtain free theatre tickets and to enter <a href="/wiki/Studio_54" title="Studio 54">Studio 54</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-fallon_76-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-fallon-76">&#91;76&#93;</a></sup> Spacey's <a href="/wiki/Capitol_Records" title="Capitol Records">Capitol</a>/<a href="/wiki/EMI" title="EMI">EMI</a> album <i><a href="/wiki/Forever_Cool" title="Forever Cool">Forever Cool</a></i> (2007) features two <a href="/wiki/Duet" title="Duet">duets</a> with Spacey and an earlier recording of <a href="/wiki/Dean_Martin" title="Dean Martin">Dean Martin</a>: "<a href="/wiki/Ain%27t_That_a_Kick_in_the_Head" class="mw-redirect" title="Ain&#39;t That a Kick in the Head">Ain't That a Kick in the Head</a>" and "<a href="/wiki/King_of_the_Road_(song)" title="King of the Road (song)">King of the Road</a>". In December 2007, Spacey co-hosted the <a href="/wiki/Nobel_Peace_Prize_Concert" title="Nobel Peace Prize Concert">Nobel Peace Prize Concert</a> along with <a href="/wiki/Uma_Thurman" title="Uma Thurman">Uma Thurman</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-77" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-77">&#91;77&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2013.E2.80.932017:_House_of_Cards_and_critical_acclaim"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2013–2017:_House_of_Cards_and_critical_acclaim">2013–2017: <i>House of Cards</i> and critical acclaim</span></h4>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_(8769358329).jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg/220px-Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="176" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg/330px-Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/25/Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg/440px-Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_%288769358329%29.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2682" data-file-height="2146" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Governor_Tours_the_House_of_Cards_Set_(8769358329).jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Spacey showing <a href="/wiki/Governor_of_Maryland" title="Governor of Maryland">Maryland governor</a> <a href="/wiki/Martin_O%27Malley" title="Martin O&#39;Malley">Martin O'Malley</a> around the set of <i>House of Cards</i>, May 2013</div></div></div>
<p>On March 18, 2011, it was announced that Spacey was cast as <a href="/wiki/Frank_Underwood_(House_of_Cards)" title="Frank Underwood (House of Cards)">Frank Underwood</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Netflix" title="Netflix">Netflix</a> series <i><a href="/wiki/House_of_Cards_(American_TV_series)" title="House of Cards (American TV series)">House of Cards</a></i>, adapted from a 1990 <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a> <a href="/wiki/House_of_Cards_(UK_TV_series)" class="mw-redirect" title="House of Cards (UK TV series)">political drama of the same name</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-78" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-78">&#91;78&#93;</a></sup> He was nominated for the <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award_for_Outstanding_Lead_Actor_in_a_Drama_Series" title="Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series">Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series</a> at the <a href="/wiki/65th_Primetime_Emmy_Awards" title="65th Primetime Emmy Awards">65th Primetime Emmy Awards</a> in 2013, becoming the first lead actor to be Primetime Emmy-nominated from a <a href="/wiki/Web_television" class="mw-redirect" title="Web television">web television</a> series.<sup id="cite_ref-NDWi2PEN_79-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NDWi2PEN-79">&#91;79&#93;</a></sup> Spacey went on to win the <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe_Award_for_Best_Actor_%E2%80%93_Television_Series_Drama" title="Golden Globe Award for Best Actor – Television Series Drama">Golden Globe award for Best Actor in a Television Series Drama</a> at the <a href="/wiki/72nd_Golden_Globe_Awards" title="72nd Golden Globe Awards">72nd Golden Globe Awards</a> and <a href="/wiki/Screen_Actors_Guild_Award_for_Outstanding_Performance_by_a_Male_Actor_in_a_Drama_Series" title="Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series">Screen Actors Guild nomination for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Drama Series</a> at the <a href="/wiki/21st_Screen_Actors_Guild_Awards" title="21st Screen Actors Guild Awards">21st Screen Actors Guild Awards</a> for his <a href="/wiki/House_of_Cards_(season_2)" title="House of Cards (season 2)">season 2</a> performance.<sup id="cite_ref-80" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-80">&#91;80&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-81" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-81">&#91;81&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2018, Earl Blue, owner of the security company VIP Protective Services, claimed that Spacey had used racial slurs against his predominantly African-American staff when they were hired on the <i>House of Cards</i> set in 2012, before getting Blue fired.<sup id="cite_ref-82" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-82">&#91;82&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h4><span id="2017.E2.80.93present:_Career_setback_and_comeback_attempts"></span><span class="mw-headline" id="2017–present:_Career_setback_and_comeback_attempts">2017–present: Career setback and comeback attempts</span></h4>
<p>Following sexual misconduct allegations from 2017, Spacey maintained a lower profile and his career stalled.<sup id="cite_ref-83" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-83">&#91;83&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-84" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-84">&#91;84&#93;</a></sup> Spacey appeared in previously shot film <i><a href="/wiki/Billionaire_Boys_Club_(2018_film)" title="Billionaire Boys Club (2018 film)">Billionaire Boys Club</a></i>, which was released in 2018 with his scenes unaltered.<sup id="cite_ref-85" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-85">&#91;85&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In May 2021, it was announced that he had been cast in a supporting role as a police detective in the crime drama film <i><a href="/wiki/The_Man_Who_Drew_God" title="The Man Who Drew God">The Man Who Drew God</a></i>, directed by and starring <a href="/wiki/Franco_Nero" title="Franco Nero">Franco Nero</a>, which is about a blind artist who is wrongly accused of sexually abusing a child.<sup id="cite_ref-ABC2021_86-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ABC2021-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:2_87-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:2-87">&#91;87&#93;</a></sup> Spacey has not commented on the role.<sup id="cite_ref-ABC2021_86-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-ABC2021-86">&#91;86&#93;</a></sup> In August 2021, it was reported that he was filming in California for a small production titled <i><a href="/wiki/Peter_Five_Eight" title="Peter Five Eight">Peter Five Eight</a></i>, directed by Michael Zaiko Hall.<sup id="cite_ref-:3_88-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:3-88">&#91;88&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-:4_89-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-:4-89">&#91;89&#93;</a></sup> In the movie, Spacey is said to be playing a charismatic <a href="/wiki/Serial_killer" title="Serial killer">serial killer</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-90" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-90">&#91;90&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>On November 3, 2022, <i>Variety</i> reported that Spacey was set to speak at the <a href="/wiki/National_Museum_of_Cinema" title="National Museum of Cinema">National Museum of Cinema</a> and was going to receive a lifetime achievement award on January 16, 2023 despite the allegations against him.<sup id="cite_ref-91" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-91">&#91;91&#93;</a></sup> On November 28, 2022, after winning a sexual battery lawsuit against him filed by Anthony Rapp, Spacey was cast in the British indie thriller <i>Control</i>. The director of the film, Gene Fallaize, dismissed concerns about working with Spacey.<sup id="cite_ref-92" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-92">&#91;92&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 2022, Spacey was cast as the late Croatian leader <a href="/wiki/Franjo_Tudjman" class="mw-redirect" title="Franjo Tudjman">Franjo Tudjman</a> in the political drama <i>Once Upon a Time in Croatia</i>, directed by <a href="/wiki/Jakov_Sedlar" title="Jakov Sedlar">Jakov Sedlar</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-93" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-93">&#91;93&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Filmography">Filmography</span></h3>
<style data-mw-deduplicate="TemplateStyles:r1033289096">.mw-parser-output .hatnote{font-style:italic}.mw-parser-output div.hatnote{padding-left:1.6em;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .hatnote i{font-style:normal}.mw-parser-output .hatnote+link+.hatnote{margin-top:-0.5em}</style><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">See also: <a href="/wiki/Kevin_Spacey_on_screen_and_stage" title="Kevin Spacey on screen and stage">Kevin Spacey on screen and stage</a></div>
<p>Spacey's career has spanned 30 years across film, television, video games and theatre. His film career started in the late 1980s after small parts in the <a href="/wiki/Mike_Nichols" title="Mike Nichols">Mike Nichols</a> films <i><a href="/wiki/Heartburn_(film)" title="Heartburn (film)">Heartburn</a></i> (1986) and <i><a href="/wiki/Working_Girl" title="Working Girl">Working Girl</a></i> (1988). In the '90s he had supporting roles in films such as <i><a href="/wiki/Glengarry_Glen_Ross_(film)" title="Glengarry Glen Ross (film)">Glengarry Glen Ross</a></i> (1992) opposite <a href="/wiki/Jack_Lemmon" title="Jack Lemmon">Jack Lemmon</a> and <a href="/wiki/Al_Pacino" title="Al Pacino">Al Pacino</a> and the <a href="/wiki/Black_comedy" title="Black comedy">black comedy</a> film <i><a href="/wiki/The_Ref" title="The Ref">The Ref</a></i> before being cast in the role of <a href="/wiki/Keyser_S%C3%B6ze" title="Keyser Söze">Roger "Verbal" Kint</a> in 1995's <i><a href="/wiki/The_Usual_Suspects" title="The Usual Suspects">The Usual Suspects</a></i>, which earned him an <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Academy Award">Academy Award</a> for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Supporting_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor">Best Supporting Actor</a>. That same year he played <a href="/wiki/Serial_killer" title="Serial killer">serial killer</a> John Doe in <i><a href="/wiki/Seven_(1995_film)" title="Seven (1995 film)">Se7en</a></i> opposite <a href="/wiki/Brad_Pitt" title="Brad Pitt">Brad Pitt</a> and <a href="/wiki/Morgan_Freeman" title="Morgan Freeman">Morgan Freeman</a>. He went on to star in noir crime drama <i><a href="/wiki/L.A._Confidential_(film)" title="L.A. Confidential (film)">L.A. Confidential</a></i> (1997) alongside <a href="/wiki/Russell_Crowe" title="Russell Crowe">Russell Crowe</a> and <a href="/wiki/Guy_Pearce" title="Guy Pearce">Guy Pearce</a>, <a href="/wiki/Clint_Eastwood" title="Clint Eastwood">Clint Eastwood</a>'s <i><a href="/wiki/Midnight_in_the_Garden_of_Good_and_Evil_(film)" title="Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil (film)">Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil</a></i> (1997), and <i><a href="/wiki/American_Beauty_(1999_film)" title="American Beauty (1999 film)">American Beauty</a></i> (1999), for which he earned his second Academy Award, this time for <a href="/wiki/Academy_Award_for_Best_Actor" title="Academy Award for Best Actor">Best Actor</a>.
</p><p>In the 2000s he appeared in the films <i><a href="/wiki/Pay_It_Forward_(film)" title="Pay It Forward (film)">Pay It Forward</a></i> with <a href="/wiki/Helen_Hunt" title="Helen Hunt">Helen Hunt</a> (2000), <i><a href="/wiki/Superman_Returns" title="Superman Returns">Superman Returns</a></i> as <a href="/wiki/Lex_Luthor" title="Lex Luthor">Lex Luthor</a> (2006), and <i><a href="/wiki/21_(2008_film)" title="21 (2008 film)">21</a></i> with <a href="/wiki/Jim_Sturgess" title="Jim Sturgess">Jim Sturgess</a> (2008), the last of which he also produced. In 2004 he wrote, directed and starred in the biopic musical <i><a href="/wiki/Beyond_the_Sea_(2004_film)" title="Beyond the Sea (2004 film)">Beyond the Sea</a></i> (2004). In 2011 he co-starred with <a href="/wiki/Paul_Bettany" title="Paul Bettany">Paul Bettany</a> and <a href="/wiki/Jeremy_Irons" title="Jeremy Irons">Jeremy Irons</a> in the drama film <i><a href="/wiki/Margin_Call" title="Margin Call">Margin Call</a></i>. That same year he played antagonist Dave Harken in the comedy <i><a href="/wiki/Horrible_Bosses" title="Horrible Bosses">Horrible Bosses</a></i> with <a href="/wiki/Jason_Bateman" title="Jason Bateman">Jason Bateman</a>, a role he reprised in the 2014 sequel film <i><a href="/wiki/Horrible_Bosses_2" title="Horrible Bosses 2">Horrible Bosses 2</a></i>. He played Doc in the 2017 film <i><a href="/wiki/Baby_Driver" title="Baby Driver">Baby Driver</a></i> with <a href="/wiki/Ansel_Elgort" title="Ansel Elgort">Ansel Elgort</a>.
</p><p>From 2013 to 2017 he played <a href="/wiki/Frank_Underwood_(House_of_Cards)" title="Frank Underwood (House of Cards)">Francis "Frank" Underwood</a> in the <a href="/wiki/Netflix" title="Netflix">Netflix</a> series <i><a href="/wiki/House_of_Cards_(American_TV_series)" title="House of Cards (American TV series)">House of Cards</a></i> alongside <a href="/wiki/Robin_Wright" title="Robin Wright">Robin Wright</a>. Spacey also starred in the <a href="/wiki/HBO" title="HBO">HBO</a> television film <i><a href="/wiki/Recount_(film)" title="Recount (film)">Recount</a></i> (2008) and produced the 2006 film <i><a href="/wiki/Bernard_and_Doris" title="Bernard and Doris">Bernard and Doris</a></i>.
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Awards_and_nominations">Awards and nominations</span></h2>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Spacey_Star.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Spacey_Star.jpg/220px-Spacey_Star.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="159" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Spacey_Star.jpg/330px-Spacey_Star.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/Spacey_Star.jpg/440px-Spacey_Star.jpg 2x" data-file-width="2555" data-file-height="1849" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Spacey_Star.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Spacey's star on the <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame" title="Hollywood Walk of Fame">Hollywood Walk of Fame</a>, laid in 1999</div></div></div>
<link rel="mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href="mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1033289096"/><div role="note" class="hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Main article: <a href="/wiki/List_of_awards_and_nominations_received_by_Kevin_Spacey" title="List of awards and nominations received by Kevin Spacey">List of awards and nominations received by Kevin Spacey</a></div>
<p>Spacey has won two <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Academy Awards</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Tony_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Tony Award">Tony Award</a>, a <a href="/wiki/Golden_Globe_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Golden Globe Award">Golden Globe Award</a>, four <a href="/wiki/Screen_Actors_Guild_Awards" title="Screen Actors Guild Awards">Screen Actors Guild Awards</a> and a <a href="/wiki/British_Academy_Film_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="British Academy Film Award">British Academy Film Award</a>. He was nominated for a <a href="/wiki/Grammy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Grammy Award">Grammy Award</a> and for 12 <a href="/wiki/Primetime_Emmy_Award" class="mw-redirect" title="Primetime Emmy Award">Primetime Emmy Awards</a>. Spacey received a star on the <a href="/wiki/Hollywood_Walk_of_Fame" title="Hollywood Walk of Fame">Hollywood Walk of Fame</a> in 1999 and was named an honorary Commander and Knight Commander of the <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">Order of the British Empire</a> in 2010 and 2015, respectively.<sup id="cite_ref-94" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-94">&#91;94&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-CBE_95-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-CBE-95">&#91;95&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-KBE_96-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-KBE-96">&#91;96&#93;</a></sup>
</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Personal_life">Personal life</span></h2><p>
An article in <i><a href="/wiki/The_Sunday_Times_Magazine" title="The Sunday Times Magazine">The Sunday Times Magazine</a></i> in 1999 stated that Spacey's "love affair with acting, and the absence of a visible partner in the life of an attractive 40-year-old, has resulted in <a href="/wiki/Esquire_(magazine)" title="Esquire (magazine)"><i>Esquire</i></a> magazine asserting two years ago that he must be <a href="/wiki/Homosexuality" title="Homosexuality">gay</a>".<sup id="cite_ref-Personal_97-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Personal-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup> Spacey responded to the rumors by telling <i><a href="/wiki/Playboy" title="Playboy">Playboy</a></i> and other interviewers that he was not gay<sup id="cite_ref-98" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-98">&#91;98&#93;</a></sup> and by telling Lesley White of <i><a href="/wiki/The_Sunday_Times" title="The Sunday Times">The Sunday Times</a></i>:</p><blockquote><p>I chose for a long time not to answer these questions because of the manner in which they were asked, and because I was never talking to someone I trusted, so why should I? Recently I chose to participate because it's a little hard on the people I love.<sup id="cite_ref-Personal_97-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Personal-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<p>In 1999, reports suggested Spacey was dating a <a href="/wiki/Script_supervisor" title="Script supervisor">script supervisor</a> named Dianne Dreyer, with their relationship possibly dating back as far as 1992.<sup id="cite_ref-Gotham_99-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotham-99">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-100" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-100">&#91;100&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-101" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-101">&#91;101&#93;</a></sup> In 2000, Spacey brought Dreyer to the <a href="/wiki/Academy_Awards" title="Academy Awards">Academy Awards</a>;<sup id="cite_ref-Gotham_99-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Gotham-99">&#91;99&#93;</a></sup> during the acceptance speech for his Best Actor award, Spacey stated, "Dianne, thank you for teaching me about caring about the right things, and I love you."<sup id="cite_ref-academy_102-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-academy-102">&#91;102&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>
In 2007, <i><a href="/wiki/Gotham_(magazine)" title="Gotham (magazine)">Gotham</a></i> magazine quoted Spacey saying:</p><blockquote><p>I've never believed in pimping my personal life out for publicity. Although I might be interested in doing it, I will never do it. People can gossip all they want; they can speculate all they want. I just happen to believe that there's a separation between the public life and the private life. Everybody has the right to a private life no matter what their professions are.<sup id="cite_ref-Personal_97-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Personal-97">&#91;97&#93;</a></sup></p></blockquote>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Political_views_and_activism">Political views and activism</span></h3>
<div class="thumb tright"><div class="thumbinner" style="width:222px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg" class="image"><img src="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg/220px-Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg" decoding="async" width="220" height="165" class="thumbimage" srcset="//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg/330px-Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg/440px-Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg 2x" data-file-width="1000" data-file-height="750" /></a> <div class="thumbcaption"><div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Kevin_Spacey_-_Clinton_Global_Citizen_2010.jpg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"></a></div>Spacey speaking during the 2010 <a href="/wiki/Clinton_Foundation#Clinton_Global_Citizen_Awards" title="Clinton Foundation">Clinton Global Citizen Awards</a></div></div></div>
<p>Spacey is a <a href="/wiki/Democratic_Party_(United_States)" title="Democratic Party (United States)">Democrat</a> and has been described as <a href="/wiki/Left-wing_politics" title="Left-wing politics">left-leaning</a> and mirroring some of those professed by his fictional character in <i>House of Cards</i>.<sup id="cite_ref-103" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-103">&#91;103&#93;</a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-104" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-104">&#91;104&#93;</a></sup>
</p><p>In 1976 Spacey worked on <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Carter" title="Jimmy Carter">Jimmy Carter</a>'s <a href="/wiki/Jimmy_Carter_1976_presidential_campaign" title="Jimmy Carter 1976 presidential campaign">1976 presidential campaign</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-105" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-105">&#91;105&#93;</a></sup>
